  "prompt": "What are the best seasonings for ground beef?",
  "response": "The best seasonings for ground beef depend heavily on what you're planning to *do* with the ground beef.  Here's a breakdown based on common uses:\n\n**General Purpose / All-Around (Great for Burgers, Meatloaf, Tacos):**\n\n*   **Salt and Pepper:**  The foundation. Don't skimp! Use good quality salt (kosher or sea salt) and freshly ground black pepper.\n*   **Garlic Powder:**  Adds a savory depth.\n*   **Onion Powder:** Similar to garlic, rounds out the flavor.\n*   **Smoked Paprika:**  Adds a subtle smokiness and color.\n*   **Dried Oregano:**  Provides a herbaceous note.\n*   **Dried Thyme:** Another earthy herb that complements beef.\n\n**Tacos & Mexican Dishes:**\n\n*   **Chili Powder:** A blend of spices, often including ancho chili, cumin, oregano, garlic powder, and sometimes paprika.  Start with a tablespoon per pound and adjust to taste.\n*   **Cumin:** Earthy and warm, a cornerstone of taco seasoning.\n*   **Cayenne Pepper:** For heat!  Add a pinch or more, depending on your preference.\n*   **Smoked Paprika:** Intensifies the smoky flavor.\n*   **Garlic Powder & Onion Powder:**  As above.\n*   **Dried Oregano:**  Mexican oregano is preferred if you can find it, but regular oregano works well too.\n\n**Burgers:**\n\n*   **Salt and Pepper:** Again, essential.\n*   **Garlic Powder:**  Subtle but impactful.\n*   **Worcestershire Sauce:**  A dash adds umami and depth.\n*   **Onion Powder/Dried Minced Onion:** Either will do, but dried minced onion adds a bit of texture.\n*   **Smoked Paprika:** For a BBQ-like flavor.\n*   **Montreal Steak Seasoning:** A pre-made blend that's popular for burgers.\n\n**Meatloaf:**\n\n*   **Salt and Pepper:** Critical.\n*   **Garlic Powder & Onion Powder:** Essential building blocks.\n*   **Dried Italian Herbs (Oregano, Basil, Thyme, Rosemary):** Adds a classic meatloaf flavor.\n*   **Worcestershire Sauce:**  Umami and depth.\n*   **Paprika:**  For color and a mild flavor.\n*   **Brown Sugar (Optional):**  A touch of sweetness balances the savory flavors.\n*   **Ketchup (Optional):**  Sometimes used as a seasoning *and* glaze.\n\n**Chili:**\n\n*   **Chili Powder:** The star of the show. Use a good quality chili powder, and experiment with different varieties (ancho, chipotle, etc.).\n*   **Cumin:**  Earthy and warm.\n*   **Cayenne Pepper:** For heat.\n*   **Smoked Paprika:** Adds depth and smokiness.\n*   **Garlic Powder & Onion Powder:** As above.\n*   **Dried Oregano:**  Often used in chili recipes.\n*   **Cocoa Powder (Optional):**  A small amount adds richness and depth.\n\n**Shepherd's Pie:**\n\n*   **Salt and Pepper:** A must-have.\n*   **Onion Powder:** Savory and aromatic.\n*   **Garlic Powder:** Complements the onion.\n*   **Dried Thyme:** Earthy and herbaceous.\n*   **Dried Rosemary:** Adds a distinct flavor that works well with lamb (if you're mixing it in) and beef.\n*   **Worcestershire Sauce:** Umami boost.\n\n**Tips for Seasoning Ground Beef:**\n\n*   **Season Generously:** Don't be afraid to use a good amount of seasoning.  Ground beef can handle it.\n*   **Season Early:**  Season the ground beef *before* you cook it. This allows the flavors to penetrate the meat.\n*   **Taste as You Go:**  Adjust the seasonings to your liking.  Add a little at a time and taste the cooked beef to see if it needs more.\n*   **Consider Other Ingredients:** Think about the other ingredients you're using in your dish. Adjust your seasonings to complement those flavors.\n*   **Fresh Herbs:**  Fresh herbs are a fantastic addition, but they're best added towards the end of cooking to preserve their flavor.\n*   **Start Simple:** If you're unsure, start with salt, pepper, garlic powder, and onion powder. You can always add more from there.\n*   **Blooming Spices:**  For maximum flavor, especially with chili powder and cumin, \"bloom\" the spices in a bit of oil before adding the ground beef.  Heat the oil over medium heat, add the spices, and cook for about a minute until fragrant.\n*   **Pre-made Blends:**  There are many excellent pre-made seasoning blends available. Just be sure to check the ingredients and adjust to your taste.\n\nNo matter what you're making, experiment and find what flavors you enjoy most!\n",
